Analysis of genotype-phenotype associations in BBS

Veronika Niederlova

11 06, 2019

Summary of the data and descriptive analysis

The data file contains the following variables:

variables description
source Source study that can be find in the manuscript.
source case n.  The ID or another information that can be used for identification of the record within the study.
gene BBS gene that contain causative mutation.
sex Sex of patient, blanks mean not available.
age group Age groups according to age, blanks mean not available.
age Specific age, if available.
RD Retinal dystrophy, 1 = present, 0 = not present, blank = not available
OBE Obesity, 1 = present, 0 = not present, blank = not available
PD Polydactyly, 1 = present, 0 = not present, blank = not available
CI Cognitive impairment, 1 = present, 0 = not present, blank = not available
REP Reproductive system anomalies, 1 = present, 0 = not present, blank = not available
REN Renal anomalies, 1 = present, 0 = not present, blank = not available
HEART Heart anomalies, 1 = present, 0 = not present, blank = not available
LIV Liver anomalies, 1 = present, 0 = not present, blank = not available
DD Developmental delay, 1 = present, 0 = not present, blank = not available
muttype Type of mutation, MSMSandMScLOF meaning missense mutation in at least one allele, cLOF meaning assumed complete loss of function mutations in both alleles
sisubset Severity score subset, yes if information about RD, OBE, PD, CI and REN is stated, no if any of these contain blanks.
ggroup Group of genes according to their function, bbs3 for mutations in BBS3, bbsome for mutations in BBS1, BBS2, BBS4, BBS5, BBS7, BBS8, BBS9 and BBS18, chaps for mutations in BBS6,BBS10 and BBS12, other for mutations in BBS11, BBS13, BBS14, BBS16, BBS17, BBS19, BBS20 and BBS21.
allwow Yes for canonical BBS genes BBS1-10, BBS12 and BBS18, no for BBS11, BBS13, BBS14, BBS16, BBS17, BBS19, BBS20 and BBS21.
canonwobbs1 Yes for canonical BBS genes other than BBS1 (BBS2-10, BBS12 and BBS18), no for BBS1, BBS11, BBS13, BBS14, BBS16, BBS17, BBS19, BBS20 and BBS21.
si syndromic score calculated as the sum of RD, OBE, PD, CI and REN divided by 5.
agegroup Age groups similar to variable age group renamed as follows: age1 = 0-9, age2 = 10-19, age3 = 20-39, age4 = 40+.
year Year of publication
m390r Indicates if the particular mutation is BBS1 M390R/M390R

Syndromic score

For the analyses in Figure 1 we use the syndromic score, which is defined in patients with reported presence/absence of the five primary phenotypic criteria (RD,OBE,PD,CI,REN). Patients with blanks in any of these categories are not used for this statistics. Let’s define the syndromic score subset called ’set and analyze the penetrance of the symptoms and penetrance of mutations in BBS genes in this ’set, as used in Figure 1B and Figure 1C.

Syndromic score in patients with cLOF vs MS mutations

Below, we will test if the syndromic score differs between patients with mutations leading to complete loss of function of the protein (such as frameshifts, splicing mutations, large deletions etc.) and patients having at least one missense mutation (either a substitution or a small deletion of one to three amino acids).

## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  subset_sscore$si by subset_sscore$muttype
## W = 18032, p-value = 0.001348
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

In addition, we will test if the proportion of patients with syndromic score of 1 differs between cLOF and missense patients. This will be tested using Fisher test on number of patients with syndromic score 1 or syndromic score other than one in both groups.

## 
##  Fisher's Exact Test for Count Data
## 
## data:  
## p-value = 0.005732
## alternative hypothesis: true odds ratio is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.3197646 0.8458189
## sample estimates:
## odds ratio 
##  0.5222815

Analysis of phenotypes

For this analysis, all available data were used, i.e. not restricted to the ’set. Statistical significance of penetrance of phenotypes was tested using Fisher test.

Phenotypes in gene groups:

First, let’s test if any differences in the penetrance of phenotypes exist between gene groups in each phenotype.

On the 5% level, differences were shown in PD, CI, REP, REN and HEART.

Let’have a look at the differences between individual groups to reveal which differences account for the overall difference. As there are 3 groups, the p-value on which we consider the difference being statistical significance will be lowered according to Sidak correction for multiple comparisons.

Analysis of cLOF subset

For this analysis, all available data were used, i.e. not restricted to the ’set. However, only patients having causative mutation of type cLOF were included. Statistical significance of penetrance of phenotypes was tested using Fisher test.
